# Inventory Analytics Framework

## Overview

Inventory analytics provides visibility into product availability, allocation performance, and stock movement across wholesale operations.

Strong inventory analytics helps operations teams ensure that orders can be fulfilled efficiently while minimizing stockouts, excess inventory, and allocation conflicts.

---

## Purpose

Inventory analytics helps organizations:

• monitor product availability  
• improve inventory allocation decisions  
• identify stockout risks  
• track inventory turnover  
• support demand planning and forecasting  

These insights allow operations teams to balance supply and demand effectively.

---

## Key Inventory Metrics

Common inventory analytics metrics include:

• inventory availability rate  
• stockout frequency  
• inventory turnover ratio  
• backorder rate  
• days of inventory on hand  

Monitoring these metrics helps organizations identify supply chain risks.

---

## Inventory Data Sources

Inventory analytics typically relies on data from:

• ERP systems  
• warehouse management systems (WMS)  
• inventory management platforms  
• sales order data  

Combining these data sources provides a complete view of inventory performance.

---

## Operational Benefits

Inventory analytics helps operations teams:

• prioritize high-demand products  
• manage inventory allocation during shortages  
• detect inventory discrepancies  
• optimize warehouse stock levels  

These improvements support more reliable order fulfillment.

---

## Final Note

Inventory analytics enables wholesale organizations to make data-driven decisions about product availability and allocation. Strong inventory visibility improves operational efficiency and customer service performance.
